EDA

Mall data is a dataframe with 5 columns and 200 rows. All Columns are double apart from gender which is character, will probably change to factor or logical. No NAs are present in the data. the Columns are:

  1. customer_id
  2. gender
  3. age
  4. annual_income_k
  5. spending_score_1_100 - presumming score is from 1 to 100.

Max annual income appears to be 137k, max spending score is 99.

mall_trim <- mall %>% 
  select(-age, -gender)
mall_trim
ggplot(mall_trim, aes(x = annual_income_k, y = spending_score_1_100)) +
  geom_point()

# scaling data
mall_scale <- mall_trim %>% 
  select(-customer_id) %>% 
  mutate(across(1:2, scale))
mall_scale


mall_scale %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = c(annual_income_k, spending_score_1_100),
               names_to = "type",
               values_to = "value") %>% 
  group_by(type) %>% 
  summarise(mean = round(mean(value)),
            sd = sd(value))
# check the plot after scaling, looks the same
ggplot(mall_scale, aes(x = annual_income_k, y = spending_score_1_100)) +
  geom_point()

Clustering

Try a few methods to see how the data clusters. Looks like five cluster groups is a good way forward.

# Elbow method
fviz_nbclust(mall_scale, 
             kmeans, 
             method = "wss", 
             nstart = 25)

# silhouette method
fviz_nbclust(mall_scale, 
             kmeans, 
             method = "silhouette", 
             nstart = 25)

fviz_nbclust(mall_scale, 
             kmeans, 
             method = "gap_stat")

Visualise the clusters

# plotting non scaled data
clusters_non_scaled <- augment(clustered_mall, mall_trim)

ggplot(clusters, aes(annual_income_k, spending_score_1_100, colour = .cluster)) +
  geom_point()

Non scaled data changes the clusters slightly, but is easier to interpret.

# looking at averages of income and speding score by cluster
clusters_non_scaled %>% 
  group_by(.cluster) %>%
  summarise(annual_income_k = mean(annual_income_k), spending_score_1_100 = mean(spending_score_1_100)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(spending_score_1_100))

Comments on clusters and Targeting

After initial exploration I settled on building 5 clusters with the data. Once K-means clustering was completed we are left with 5 clusters as summarised above. The results are interesting from a targeting point of view.

The two highest average earners, clusters 3 and 4, are separated by under 2k in earnings but the spending scores are very different, with the cluster that earns slightly less (4) scoring significantly higher. Cluster 4 actually has the highest average spending score (82) in the dataset. I would suggest targeting this cluster in the first instance.

As a second target group I would go with cluster 5 which although having the second lowest average income, has the second highest spending score (66).

Overall in terms of targeting based on spending score I would go for the following order: 4, 5, 2, 1, 3.
